Government is fixing the roof by taking tiles from other houses
'it hardly seems like we are fixing the roof while the sun shines. The Government is cutting its borrowing by getting households to borrow more'
'The issue is that the growth is coming from consumers spending money they don’t have.' Photo: Alastair Grant/PA	By Rob Wood
6:22PM GMT 05 Dec 2013
Comments
A good day for George Osborne. In his Autumn Statement the Chancellor lowered the government borrowing forecasts for the first time in three years on the back of faster growth. The problem is that the better outlook is being bought with unbalanced growth. The government may be fixing its roof, but could also be building a less, rather than a more resilient, economy. Forget all the announced policies today, which were generally small and net off against each other. Osborne banked the gains from stronger growth, cutting the deficit by a cumulative £73bn over the next five years. That was the right strategy. Borrowing is better but it is hardly good. The deficit is expected to be £96bn next year. Today’s changes just undo the damage of the last 12 months of disappointing numbers. Osborne deserves credit for trying to deal with the longer-term issues. With continued austerity and a fair wind – and another Conservative government, Osborne would add – the deficit should be eliminated by 2019. Planning to raise the retirement age was also necessary, if not welcome for the under-40s affected. Cutting National Insurance contributions for under 21 year-olds was also sensible. Related Articles
