05 Dec 2013
Autumn Statement 2013: winners and losers
05 Dec 2013
Autumn Statement 2013: key points
05 Dec 2013
Sketch: A case of smirk and mirrors
05 Dec 2013
The issue is that the growth is coming from consumers spending money they don’t have. Stronger consumption explains much of the better growth outlook. In turn, that is because households are saving less and re-leveraging. The Office for Budget Responsibility expects household debt to rise to 160pc of income by 2018 and house prices to get close to their bubble time peak by 2018, in real times. This all stacks up, given the reliance on monetary policy to get the economy moving. But it hardly seems like we are fixing the roof while the sun shines. More like fixing the government’s roof by taking tiles from others' houses. The Government is cutting its borrowing by getting households to borrow more. A resurgent housing market is boosting stamp duty. VAT is rising as retail spending grows. Without households dipped into their saving over the past 12 months, there would be a lot less money flowing into the government’s coffers. For the government to borrow less, someone else has to take some of the responsibility for getting the economy growing. But it feels like this is an option we tried before the crisis with, to put it mildly, less than stellar results. It isn’t all bad. It would be churlish not to welcome lower government borrowing, a recovering economy and falling unemployment. Growth is better than stagnation even if it comes from households initially. Indeed, returning confidence may kick-start some more spending by businesses and a return to rising productivity. The government has not been totally idle either. It has cut corporation tax substantially, for instance. Today is a day to be pleased today with the improving deficit outlook and measures to deal with the poor longer-term debt trajectory. But tomorrow will be time to look for measures to move away from this unbalanced growth over the next year. In fairness, the Bank of England started trying to dial things down a notch by cancelling part of the Funding for Lending Scheme that was spraying cheap funding at any bank that would take it. That is likely to be the first in a series of measures from the financial policymakers. The Help-to-Buy scheme should be scrapped, the government should be doing much more to boost housebuilding. The £1bn offered in today’s statement is not enough. More broadly UK infrastructure spending is woefully short of what is required. The to-do list is long. Lets not wait too long before getting cracking. Rob Wood is UK economist at Berenberg Bank and former economist at the Bank of England
