Tricks that save up to £500 on a holiday
It is a game of brinkmanship as tour operators and agents aim to sell all their holidays at the best price. Our tips give you the upper hand Dream holiday: cut hundreds of pounds off the cost of your trip by researching the market thoroughly and then haggling for a better deal By Nicole Blackmore
7:06AM GMT 14 Jan 2014
Follow Comments
January is the busiest time of the year for holiday bookings thanks to the gloomy weather and post-Christmas slump. Tour operators and travel agents feverishly compete for your business with promises of discounts and special deals. But it is a game of brinkmanship. Companies want to extract the maximum from customers but also don’t want to be left with unsold holidays. Which package deals are best?
Package holidays remain the most popular type of booking, according to Abta, the travel trade association, with 46pc of holidaymakers – 16.5million people – buying that way. They are bought either directly, from tour operators such as Thomson and Thomas Cook, or through a travel agent. The holiday – with flights, transfers, accommodation and sometimes food included – are Atol protected. This means that if your travel company fails, you will be entitled to a refund if you are yet to travel, and hotel costs and flights home if you are already abroad. Related Articles
