Thorough research is essential when booking. Prices for the same holiday can vary, even when offered by brands owned by the same company. Sometimes this is because services and extras, perhaps unwanted, are added on. Our research found that the cheapest deal on a week’s all-inclusive holiday for a family of four in Ibiza in late July with First Choice was £3,855. But the same break – same hotel and same flights – cost £3,388 via Thomson, a saving of £467. Both are owned by Tui Travel. First Choice markets the resort as one of its upmarket “Holiday Villages”. The more expensive holiday offers a sea view. Once you have an online price, use it to your advantage. Haggling is still alive and well in the holiday industry so contact rival providers or travel agents to see if they can beat it. Agents also offer holidays they have put together, made up of flights, accommodation and extras such as car hire, provided by different companies. These are not traditional package holidays, but agents often refer to them as such. New rules introduced last year mean these holidays are Atol protected if the flight and either the hotel or car hire are booked within one day of each another. But flights only, booked through a travel agent or direct with airlines, are not protected under Atol. Is it cheaper to book your own?
Travel agents and tour operators claim their buying power brings down the cost. For the particular holiday you want, only research will tell you which is cheaper. DIY holidays are a good option if you want to travel for an extended or unusual period but holidaymakers are left with little protection if the airline or hotel goes bust. How should you pay?
Paying with a credit card can offer additional protection in the event that your travel company goes bust. You should be able to get your money back for payments of up to £30,000. However, credit card issuers will not help you get home if you are abroad when the company goes out of business. But buying with a credit card often comes at a cost, with firms commonly charging a fee of 2pc, sometimes 3pc. First Choice and Thomson cap the charge at £95. Some companies, such as travel agent Trailfinders and tour operator Toucan, charge nothing. If you have a Visa debit card, which does not usually incur a booking fee, ask your bank whether you are covered under “chargeback”, a voluntary policy. Also check whether your travel insurance covers you for losses if your holiday provider goes bust. The insurance traps to avoid
Carefully check terms and conditions. Many travel insurance policies do not cover losses if a holiday company goes bust, which leaves DIY holidaymakers exposed. Cancellation cover can also vary significantly between insurers. Some policies will cover only losses caused by cancellation due to personal illness. Richard Young, 66, of Gosport, Hampshire, booked a trip to Italy and took out insurance with Staysure. He was travelling with his choir, the Portsmouth Choral Union, which was giving a number of performances. Mr Young was due to fly on May 24 from Heathrow to Bologna with British Airways. However, BA cancelled a number of scheduled flights following an incident at the airport. Mr Young, who is a retired serviceman, was unable to book a later flight and was forced to abandon his trip. BA refunded the cost of the flight, £211, but denied any liability for additional losses. Mr Young contacted Staysure and lodged a claim for his accommodation and pre-booked excursion costs, which totalled £584. Staysure rejected the claim, saying the policy did not cover losses due to flight cancellation. “Staysure said it would have covered the cancellation if I was poorly and couldn’t travel, but not a cancellation that was out of my control,” Mr Young said. “Is it appropriate that a policy should make such an exclusion? I did not miss the trip because of my own stupidity or sloth. Should I be left to bear the financial burden of BA’s decision? ”
Staysure said it was important for customers to check when they took out a travel insurance policy what expenses would and wouldn’t be covered. However, a spokesman said there might have been an error in Mr Young’s case and promised to review his claim. Richard Young and his wife Celia When is the best time to book?
If you must travel during school holidays, grab summer holiday deals in January or before. If you don’t book early, consider leaving it to the last minute instead. Tour operators and travel agents often slash their prices a month or so before departure. You will have less choice, but the chances of grabbing a bargain are high. One trick for the most dedicated bargain hunters is to watch out for trading updates from the big tour operators. Thomas Cook, for example, will disclose its sales performance on February 11. Disappointment could mean a sale of last-minute holidays. Save money on flights by booking in advance and flying midweek. Analysis of pricing data suggests it is cheapest to fly on a Tuesday, as long as you book 59 days in advance, according to Moneysavingexpert.com. There are a number of websites that help you identify the cheapest flights – comparison website momondo.co.uk has a tool called Flight Insight that lets you interrogate specific data for 150 popular routes, while Kayak.co.uk has a tool that predicts whether the cost of the flight you want is likely to go up or down over the next seven days. Cheaper spending when you're there...
CARDS Banks and building societies charge up to 3pc for foreign transactions. So apply now for a specialist overseas credit card that offers a good exchange rate with no withdrawal fees. The best card is Halifax Clarity. It has no foreign exchange fee anywhere in the world, so you get the best rate possible. It also doesn’t charge a fee for withdrawing cash from ATMs, but you will be charged interest on withdrawals. If you don’t want to take out a credit card or don’t have a good enough credit rating to qualify for the best deals, consider a prepaid card. They are a good way to control your budget and can be replaced and re-credited if lost or stolen. You pay the exchange rate offered on the day you load the card, not at the time of purchase, so there are no surprises. FairFX and CaxtonFX are good options. CASH
Few travel money firms make a direct charge but the exchange rates, through which they take their cut, vary considerably. Retailers are muscling in. Debenhams, Tesco, Sainsbury’s and Asda are all offering impressive rates this week. However, to get the best deals buyers should always order online and then collect. Even airport bureaus can be competitive if you order ahead. The rates at the window, however, are priced for desperate travellers with no other option. Compare rates at travelmoneymax.com. Consumer Tips
